Barely a month to the presidential primaries of the People’s Democratic Party (PDP), the former Vice President Atiku Abubakar has called on the leadership of the party that he deserved the right of first refusal for the party’s 2023 presidential ticket. Daily Independent had on Tuesday reported that the opposition PDPP will on Friday, May 29 begin the screening exercise of its 17 presidential aspirants ahead of the primary election slated for May 28 and 29. Atiku, while speaking during his visit to the National Working Committee (NWC) of the party in Abuja on Thursday said he has over 11 million votes in his kitty to help the party return to power in 2023. The PDP 2019 Presidential candidate, who commended the party leadership for allowing others to contest, insisted that he deserve the right of first refusal. According to him, “I deserve the right of first refusal”. Other presidential aspirants jostling for the party’s presidential ticket ahead of the 2023 general elections are former Senate President Bukola Saraki, former Anambra State Governor, Peter Obi, Governor Bala Mohammed of Bauchi State and Sokoto State Governor Aminu Tambuwal. Governor Nyesom Wike of Rivers State, former Secretary to the Government of the Federation (SGF) Pius Anyim, Akwa Ibom State Governor Udom Emmanuel, former Ekiti State Governor Ayo Fayose, Cosmos Ndukwe, Charles Ugwu, Chikwendu Kalu and Tariele Diana Oliver. Also on the list are renowned industrialist Mazi Sam Ohuabunwa, a former bank chief, Mohammed Hayatu-Deen, a United States-based medical doctor, Nwachukwu Anakwenze and Ovation Magazine publisher Dele Momodu.